1
00:00:02,157 --> 00:00:09,606
Tonight I'd like to look at one of the Buddha's teachings which addresses something we all enjoy very much, thinking.

2
00:00:11,448 --> 00:00:18,158
The Sutta is called Two Kinds of Thought, sometimes known as the simile of the cowherd.

3
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:20,942
Here are the opening words.

4
00:00:22,086 --> 00:00:33,661
Because before my enlightenment, when I was still only an unenlightened bodhisattva, it occurred to me, suppose that I divide my thoughts into two classes.

5
00:00:34,783 --> 00:00:41,271
Then I set on one side thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill will and thoughts of cruelty.

6
00:00:42,332 --> 00:00:50,203
And I set on the other side thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill will and thoughts of non-cruelty.

7
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:59,151
And as I abided thus, diligent, ardent and resolute, a thought of sensual desire arose in me.

8
00:01:00,453 --> 00:01:05,319
I understood thus, this thought of sensual desire has arisen in me.

9
00:01:06,540 --> 00:01:12,349
This leads to my own affliction, to others' affliction and to the affliction of both.

10
00:01:13,631 --> 00:01:18,638
It obstructs wisdom, causes difficulties and leads away from Nibbana.

11
00:01:19,849 --> 00:01:26,096
When I considered, this leads to my own affliction, the thought subsided in me.

12
00:01:27,578 --> 00:01:32,221
When I considered, this leads to others' affliction, it subsided in me.

13
00:01:33,504 --> 00:01:38,668
When I considered, this leads to the affliction of both, it subsided in me.

14
00:01:40,189 --> 00:01:48,978
When I considered, this obstructs wisdom, causes difficulties and leads away from Nibbana, it subsided in me.

15
00:01:50,292 --> 00:02:03,498
He then goes on to say the same about thoughts of ill-will and thoughts of cruelty.

16
00:02:05,902 --> 00:02:09,870
Our first task is to recognise thoughts of sensual desire.

17
00:02:10,441 --> 00:02:16,927
These would be prompting us to get more of the pleasures of the five senses and get away from their painful aspects.

18
00:02:17,989 --> 00:02:30,581
I'm also going to include the sixth sense of the mind here, as it's a huge area of sense desire, perhaps even more so nowadays than in the Buddha's time, with all our many choices for entertainment.

19
00:02:33,223 --> 00:02:36,668
Let's start with the pleasures and pains of food.

20
00:02:37,610 --> 00:03:05,742
Think of how much time, energy and other resources society pours into the food industry, the agricultural sector itself, distribution, supermarkets, restaurants, bakeries and numerous other food outlets and on top of that we have cookbooks, restaurant reviews, TV shows, the Great British Bake Off, not to speak of all the advertisement needed to sell each packet of biscuits and each carton of orange juice.

21
00:03:05,723 --> 00:03:11,852
Even our pets have to get tasty morsels that have been through huge industrial processing and packaging.

22
00:03:13,955 --> 00:03:18,341
With all that activity around us, how can we avoid thinking about food?

23
00:03:19,984 --> 00:03:22,366
But not every thought about food is unwholesome.

24
00:03:23,368 --> 00:03:29,858
We need to eat and there's no harm in thinking about what will be best to eat and what we can afford and so on.

25
00:03:30,209 --> 00:03:35,478
And sharing a meal is a way of celebrating, expressing friendship, gratitude, appreciation.

26
00:03:36,560 --> 00:03:39,824
So we can happily devote time and energy to those preparations.

27
00:03:41,747 --> 00:03:45,334
What we need to look out for are thoughts leading towards indulgence.

28
00:03:47,037 --> 00:03:53,989
If our thoughts are blowing up a bubble of hedonic pleasure, then they are being driven by sense desire.

29
00:03:56,467 --> 00:03:59,653
Suppose you plan to bake a cake for a birthday celebration.

30
00:04:00,776 --> 00:04:09,955
Naturally, you need to think about the relative merits of carrot cake and black forest gato and lemon sponge, and which kind of icing will let you put candles on top.

31
00:04:10,997 --> 00:04:13,242
Lots and lots of thoughts to keep track of here.

32
00:04:14,371 --> 00:04:19,081
Mindfulness lets you detect when the hedonic bubble is starting to form.

33
00:04:20,464 --> 00:04:29,004
Some tightness will develop in your body as your system starts to curl itself around pleasant feelings generated by all these lovely thoughts.

34
00:04:30,317 --> 00:04:34,206
Remember the pleasure is absolutely fine and to be welcomed.

35
00:04:35,649 --> 00:04:46,976
Joy is part of the spiritual path and in this case we have the joy of mudita coming from your friendship with the birthday person and the wish for their continued happiness.

36
00:04:50,163 --> 00:05:03,685
The danger, however, is that we forget all about the birthday person and start to insist that we make the best ever birthday cake with a background assumption of being the best cook or the best friend anyone could ever wish for.

37
00:05:03,704 --> 00:05:08,812
A brief aside here to tie in with the teaching on the floods.

38
00:05:08,793 --> 00:05:24,413
What started off as the flood of sensuality in the form of the birthday cake has swept us away into the flood of views revolving around how to make the best cake and the flood of becoming which whirls us into being the best cook and the best friend.

39
00:05:25,435 --> 00:05:29,420
This is one reason it can be hard to identify thoughts of sensual desire.

40
00:05:30,523 --> 00:05:37,331
The thought we might notice could be something like I have to do this for Mary because she's such a lovely person.

41
00:05:38,088 --> 00:05:41,435
Hard to label this as an unwholesome thought.

42
00:05:43,158 --> 00:05:46,666
One telltale is the insistence, I have to do this.

43
00:05:47,689 --> 00:05:56,146
If we look a bit deeper, we'll find some stress underlying this, signifying that we're being swept into one or other of the floods.

44
00:05:57,814 --> 00:06:07,105
If we don't notice the flood it will provide a pleasant bubble of energy to get us through the business of shopping and baking but at some stage the bubble will burst.

45
00:06:07,966 --> 00:06:14,533
Perhaps the cake flops or the party has to be cancelled or no one gives us any praise or thanks for all our efforts.

46
00:06:15,954 --> 00:06:20,720
Even if everything goes perfectly and we get lots of praise the party will eventually end.

47
00:06:21,661 --> 00:06:26,927
The only thing to sustain our bubble is to search for another birthday and to offer to make another cake.

48
00:06:28,797 --> 00:06:36,329
This is an example of the kind of affliction the Buddha asks us to consider, since pleasures cannot ultimately satisfy us.

49
00:06:38,173 --> 00:06:46,906
If we succumb to the societal delusion that food is a real source of happiness, then we are on the road to dukkha in one form or another.

50
00:06:47,882 --> 00:07:07,129
Overweight, cardiac problems, diabetes, food fetishes are all associated with this delusion, as well as psychological stress as our persona becomes embroiled in the food business, being the best cook, frequenting only the best restaurants, food anxieties and so on.

51
00:07:08,430 --> 00:07:16,742
I know someone who, despite being several thousand euros in debt, insisted on having the most expensive brand of orange juice for his breakfast every morning.

52
00:07:18,004 --> 00:07:20,867
What starts as a pleasure turns into addiction.

53
00:07:23,750 --> 00:07:27,694
Going back to the advice from this sutta, we can nip all this in the bud.

54
00:07:28,834 --> 00:07:41,206
As we're planning and making the birthday cake, we watch for thoughts with giveaway phrases like, the best, fantastic, absolutely must have, and recognize that these stem from sensual desire.

55
00:07:42,267 --> 00:07:47,892
The Buddha's advice is simply to repeat, this thought will lead to my affliction.

56
00:07:47,872 --> 00:07:49,074
and see what happens.

57
00:07:50,177 --> 00:07:52,802
It's a gentle approach to working with sense desire.

58
00:07:53,723 --> 00:07:55,185
We're not condemning ourselves.

59
00:07:55,966 --> 00:07:59,273
We're not making ourselves miserable about the cake and the celebration.

60
00:08:00,355 --> 00:08:01,737
We're not quelling joy.

61
00:08:01,797 --> 00:08:06,725
We're just being careful that it doesn't lead to the miseries of addiction.

62
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:11,584
We can work in the same way with all sensual pleasures.

63
00:08:12,586 --> 00:08:24,107
The joy and pride we can build out of all our material possessions, our health, youth, beauty, our relationships, sexual joys, love of music and art.

64
00:08:26,071 --> 00:08:28,774
And, of course, there are the pleasures of the mind.

65
00:08:30,317 --> 00:08:33,202
Most perilous are alcohol and drug addictions.

66
00:08:33,875 --> 00:08:38,302
But temptations also come from the numerous forms of entertainment on offer nowadays.

67
00:08:38,943 --> 00:08:48,942
Books, magazines, newspapers, films, TV, internet, as well as the world of ideas and fantasy we can generate within our own minds.

68
00:08:50,725 --> 00:08:52,929
We can get addicted to any of these.

69
00:08:54,547 --> 00:09:13,517
On the other hand, we can use them well to stimulate and broaden our minds, to keep in touch with the world, to see where and how we might contribute to society, for enjoyment, as a way of relaxing, to give ourselves a treat, as a social activity.

70
00:09:16,518 --> 00:09:26,506
Too often though, we just switch on the TV or check our emails out of boredom or mindless habit rather than with a specific beneficial aim in mind.

71
00:09:27,587 --> 00:09:28,948
This is a real danger.

72
00:09:30,409 --> 00:09:42,100
The Buddha included idle gossip in his list for wrong speech and if we're just passing the time with books, internet, TV, this is the modern day equivalent of idle gossip.

73
00:09:43,301 --> 00:09:46,203
We're filling our minds because we don't like them to be empty.

74
00:09:49,153 --> 00:09:50,517
Let's look at an example.

75
00:09:51,879 --> 00:09:59,855
While studying this Suta, I'm embarrassed to admit that I was also hooked on a soap opera on Irish television called Fair City.

76
00:10:00,996 --> 00:10:07,450
But it made such a good illustration of working with this teaching that I decided to spill the beans.

77
00:10:07,429 --> 00:10:08,892
I'm blaming my mother, by the way.

78
00:10:09,873 --> 00:10:14,880
She's an avid fan, and to keep her company, I started watching occasionally.

79
00:10:16,101 --> 00:10:27,357
But when I was tempted to pre-record all the episodes I would miss while away in Satipanya, I had to admit that sensual desire had overtaken my dutiful daughter role.

80
00:10:29,301 --> 00:10:36,171
During a meditation session, I got distracted into rehashing the plot, hoping Ciarán wouldn't murder Katie.

81
00:10:37,179 --> 00:10:42,107
I decided to use this opportunity to follow the Buddha's advice in this Sutta.

82
00:10:43,269 --> 00:10:47,336
So I said to myself, this thought will lead to my affliction.

83
00:10:49,379 --> 00:10:58,192
My mind gave a kind of an uh-huh response, a fairly neutral acknowledgement of the suggestion without much reaction one way or another.

84
00:10:59,855 --> 00:11:04,182
I then reflected, this thought will lead to the affliction of others.

85
00:11:05,293 --> 00:11:07,822
At this suggestion, my ears seemed to break up.

86
00:11:08,967 --> 00:11:14,206
It seems my psyche is more worried about causing others a problem than it is at causing problems for myself.

87
00:11:16,094 --> 00:11:20,559
By the way, my psyche has got things wrong here, according to the Buddha.

88
00:11:20,580 --> 00:11:23,423
Deep down, we are most interested in our own happiness.

89
00:11:24,666 --> 00:11:28,431
And even though this might sound selfish, it's actually very wise.

90
00:11:29,532 --> 00:11:34,960
We can wish that others be happy, and that wish, if sincere, makes us happy.

91
00:11:35,941 --> 00:11:38,845
But we can't make anyone else happy.

92
00:11:39,955 --> 00:11:46,527
It's only because we get over-attached to friends and family that we believe their happiness is more important than our own.

93
00:11:47,909 --> 00:11:51,034
The psychological term is, I believe, codependency.

94
00:11:51,897 --> 00:11:53,559
Living life to please others.

95
00:11:55,767 --> 00:12:00,196
We get over-anxious about them, fuss around them, trying to make things perfect.

96
00:12:01,278 --> 00:12:03,523
Hopefully your psyche doesn't suffer in this way.

97
00:12:04,364 --> 00:12:08,974
And when you do the experiment, hopefully you will find your ears pricking up for the first phrase.

98
00:12:09,774 --> 00:12:11,599
This thought leads to my affliction.

99
00:12:13,789 --> 00:12:15,852
I then repeated the third phrase.

100
00:12:16,634 --> 00:12:19,817
This thought leads to the affliction of both myself and others.

101
00:12:21,059 --> 00:12:29,731
The uh-huh response relating to my own affliction now became energized as if it had been infected by the concern for others' affliction.

102
00:12:31,354 --> 00:12:35,460
I could sense myself querying what affliction I might be causing for myself.

103
00:12:36,942 --> 00:12:45,611
Rather than dwell on that question, I relaxed and let go, simply noticing the slightly perplexed mind state that had been engendered.

104
00:12:46,832 --> 00:12:49,056
Finally, I moved on to the reflection.

105
00:12:49,996 --> 00:12:55,363
This thought obscures wisdom, causes difficulties, leads away from Nibbana.

106
00:12:56,924 --> 00:12:59,086
At this, remorse was stirred.

107
00:12:59,927 --> 00:13:01,330
I could see the truth of it.

108
00:13:02,389 --> 00:13:10,245
I had started the meditation session ardent and resolute, but had then become completely submerged in the plight of Katie and Ciarán.

109
00:13:11,469 --> 00:13:14,313
I could very clearly see this as a loss.

110
00:13:15,557 --> 00:13:18,001
I had ruined something quite precious.

111
00:13:21,221 --> 00:13:25,528
From this brief experiment I could already see the value of this teaching.

112
00:13:26,730 --> 00:13:31,296
All three phrases had the effect of interrupting my fair city narrative.

113
00:13:32,576 --> 00:13:41,570
Each phrase had evoked a different response and I can imagine that the most effective phrase will vary depending on the particular circumstances.

114
00:13:45,855 --> 00:13:49,120
The reflection linking my own and others affliction

115
00:13:49,419 --> 00:13:52,082
is not simply a repetition of the earlier two.

116
00:13:53,364 --> 00:14:02,134
Some of us may have a wise concern for our own safety but have not transferred this to a concern for others, or vice versa.

117
00:14:03,075 --> 00:14:10,442
By combining the thought of self and other, we're letting wisdom flow from the more developed root into the less developed one.

118
00:14:12,144 --> 00:14:18,971
Of the three phrases, it was the third one which rung most true for me in this particular situation.

119
00:14:21,178 --> 00:14:29,703
Afterwards, I found myself wanting more clarity on the afflictions caused to myself or others by getting addicted to Fair City.

120
00:14:31,067 --> 00:14:34,913
On reflection, I could see that it was starting to shape my day.

121
00:14:34,953 --> 00:14:40,061
What things I'd need to have done before 8pm, what time I should eat.

122
00:14:40,822 --> 00:14:47,832
And if anyone called just before 8pm or during the next sacred half hour, my heart would not leap for joy.

123
00:14:48,975 --> 00:14:57,868
Basically, the attachment was causing stress, taking priority over more beneficial activities, getting in the way of friendships.

124
00:14:59,485 --> 00:15:07,197
To the extent that we're tied up with any addiction, we devalue our friends and family, as well as our own welfare.

125
00:15:08,359 --> 00:15:09,681
The addiction comes first.

126
00:15:10,402 --> 00:15:11,744
These come second.

127
00:15:13,025 --> 00:15:18,653
We deepen our addictions with every stray thought that finds delight in whatever it is we're attached to.

128
00:15:18,714 --> 00:15:24,462
To clarify this, the Buddha makes this striking and often quoted statement.

129
00:15:26,384 --> 00:15:33,397
Whatever Abiku frequently thinks and ponders upon, that will become the inclination of his mind.

130
00:15:35,802 --> 00:15:44,256
Every thought about Ciarán and Katie deepens my attachment to Fair City and increases the power that sensual desire holds over my psyche.

131
00:15:45,500 --> 00:15:49,927
Every time we nurse grievances, we strengthen our tendencies toward ill-will.

132
00:15:51,072 --> 00:15:56,062
Whenever we delight in thoughts of vengeance, we increase the power of cruelty in our minds.

133
00:15:57,264 --> 00:15:59,009
A sobering reflection indeed.

134
00:16:00,230 --> 00:16:10,211
We should often remind ourselves of the Buddha's statement, whatever a bhikkhu frequently thinks and ponders upon, that will become the inclination of his mind.

135
00:16:12,519 --> 00:16:22,650
Now it may well happen that the moment we notice ourselves getting caught up in thoughts about fair city, birthday cake or whatever, we immediately judge ourselves for this.

136
00:16:24,133 --> 00:16:32,081
By contrast, the Buddha doesn't judge the sense pleasure or judge himself for having thoughts of sense desire.

137
00:16:33,202 --> 00:16:36,726
He describes a completely open-minded inquiry.

138
00:16:37,988 --> 00:16:41,312
He knew better than to waste time condemning himself.

139
00:16:41,831 --> 00:16:49,384
His energies were always clearly directed towards letting go, moving on, inclining towards Nibbana.

140
00:16:52,912 --> 00:16:58,522
But many of us 21st century Westerners easily succumb to self-judgment.

141
00:16:59,644 --> 00:17:04,853
If we want to do the experiment recommended by the Buddha, we have to let go of this.

142
00:17:05,845 --> 00:17:15,114
But of course, this can't be done by willpower, saying, now I want to examine sense-desire objectively, so can I please stop judging this, at least for a few minutes?

143
00:17:16,535 --> 00:17:28,906
Instead, we have to be very patient, letting our attention dwell on the sense of judgment with an open, curious spirit, until, in the gaze of awareness, it starts to dissipate.

144
00:17:30,868 --> 00:17:35,093
Judgment, in my experience, feels oppressive and restricting.

145
00:17:36,388 --> 00:17:45,221
Physical energies come downward through the skull, pressing on the forehead and face, causing tension, heaviness and squeezing sensations.

146
00:17:47,967 --> 00:17:54,516
If I relax around all these sensations to any degree, I am then in a better position to try the Buddha's experiment.

147
00:17:55,538 --> 00:18:02,868
By then, thoughts about birthday cake or fair city will have abated, but we can reflect in a more general way.

148
00:18:04,080 --> 00:18:07,328
Thoughts of sense desire lead to my affliction.

149
00:18:08,673 --> 00:18:12,442
We're not hammering this into ourselves as an absolute truth, remember.

150
00:18:13,144 --> 00:18:18,478
We're introducing it to our minds as a thought and seeing what effect it has.

151
00:18:21,022 --> 00:18:24,688
A useful image is that of throwing a stone into a pool of water.

152
00:18:25,670 --> 00:18:30,317
The stone is the phrase, thoughts of sensual desire lead to my affliction.

153
00:18:31,178 --> 00:18:32,599
The pool is your mind.

154
00:18:33,641 --> 00:18:37,006
The stone disappears and you just watch the ripples.

155
00:18:38,048 --> 00:18:44,938
When the ripples subside, we can throw in another stone with the next phrase and so on for each phrase.

156
00:18:46,268 --> 00:18:55,882
If we repeat this faithfully, whenever we find ourselves thinking about whatever sense pleasure has got us hooked, we're undermining attachment with wisdom.

157
00:18:55,922 --> 00:18:59,247
It's a gentle way of working with attachment.

158
00:19:00,088 --> 00:19:01,510
We're not beating ourselves up.

159
00:19:02,172 --> 00:19:07,720
We're just asking our minds to acknowledge the burden that goes with any attachment.

160
00:19:09,640 --> 00:19:17,470
But we do need to be vigilant not to let new thoughts capture us and start blowing up the hedonic bubble again.

161
00:19:17,490 --> 00:19:21,253
The Buddha gives a vivid image for this.

162
00:19:23,116 --> 00:19:38,095
Just as in the last month of the rainy season, in the autumn, when the crops thicken, a cowherd would guard his cows by constantly tapping and poking them on this side and that with a stick to check and curb them.

163
00:19:38,075 --> 00:19:38,896
Why is that?

164
00:19:39,940 --> 00:19:47,278
Because he sees that he could be flogged, imprisoned, fined or blamed if he lets them stray into the crops.

165
00:19:48,241 --> 00:19:54,176
So too I saw in unwholesome states danger, degradation and defilement.

166
00:19:56,451 --> 00:19:58,015
There are two components to this.

167
00:19:58,855 --> 00:20:03,064
Firstly, the vigilance required to keep poking and prodding our unwholesome thoughts.

168
00:20:03,984 --> 00:20:07,852
We prod and poke with reflections like, this leads to my affliction.

169
00:20:08,814 --> 00:20:16,366
When we're at leisure, untroubled by sensual desire, we need to reflect on what affliction exactly we're referring to.

170
00:20:16,346 --> 00:20:27,239
This is what I was prompted to do after the exercise, to examine my life and see exactly how much stress was being caused by my attachment to Fair City.

171
00:20:28,319 --> 00:20:31,002
I had to admit that the attachment was really degrading.

172
00:20:31,943 --> 00:20:40,633
Squeezing activities like DAMA study into the has-to-be-done-before-8pm slot is quite disgraceful when I think about it.

173
00:20:40,613 --> 00:20:48,161
I'm well aware of the beneficial effect Dhamma study has on my psyche, whereas the plots in Fair City are rarely uplifting.

174
00:20:49,321 --> 00:21:00,153
The more we can clarify for ourselves that sensual desire is indeed a state of danger, degradation and defilement, the more determined we will be to avoid its superficial attraction.

175
00:21:02,035 --> 00:21:07,380
The exercise is exactly the same with regard to thoughts of ill-will and cruelty.

176
00:21:07,951 --> 00:21:18,305
In my own experience, however, it needs more time and patience to get any degree of objectivity on these thoughts, as my judgmental reaction is so much stronger in these areas.

177
00:21:19,425 --> 00:21:28,919
For this reason, I find it easier to work with the second half of the Buddha's advice, which involves recognising thoughts of non-ill will and non-cruelty.

178
00:21:29,920 --> 00:21:31,241
Here are his words.

179
00:21:33,247 --> 00:21:40,055
As I abided thus, diligent, ardent and resolute, a thought of non-ill-will arose in me.

180
00:21:41,037 --> 00:21:42,218
I understood thus.

181
00:21:43,519 --> 00:21:46,022
This thought of non-ill-will has arisen in me.

182
00:21:47,203 --> 00:21:52,790
This does not lead to my affliction, or to others' affliction, or to the affliction of both.

183
00:21:53,832 --> 00:21:58,478
It aids wisdom, does not cause difficulty, leads to Nibbāna.

184
00:22:00,500 --> 00:22:06,028
He says the same of thoughts of non-cruelty as well as the renunciation of sensual desire.

185
00:22:07,951 --> 00:22:17,984
Most of us would think of metta and compassion as the opposites of ill-will and cruelty, while the concepts non-ill-will and non-cruelty are unfamiliar.

186
00:22:18,843 --> 00:22:24,789
We find it hard to dwell on or value the fact of simply not wishing each other harm.

187
00:22:25,951 --> 00:22:36,744
But this links to delusion, the way we obscure our Buddha nature and fail to see the happiness on offer when we rest in simplicity, without desires for this and that.

188
00:22:37,885 --> 00:22:44,934
Nibbana, remember, can be described as not this, not that, as in this passage from the Udana.

189
00:22:46,096 --> 00:22:57,112
There is that dimension where there is neither earth, nor water, nor fire, nor wind, neither this world, nor the next world, nor sun, nor moon.

190
00:23:01,858 --> 00:23:05,785
Metta and compassion are the worldly expressions of Nibbana.

191
00:23:07,106 --> 00:23:12,795
They are the enlightened response to samsaric beings like us, who need friendliness and compassion.

192
00:23:14,075 --> 00:23:20,780
But the path to metta and compassion, according to the Buddha, requires first a withdrawal from ill-will and cruelty.

193
00:23:22,041 --> 00:23:26,405
We might tend to dismiss that state of withdrawal as somehow unimportant.

194
00:23:26,787 --> 00:23:42,681
However, in this sutta, the Buddha tells us that he spent time looking for thoughts associated with non-ill-will and non-cruelty, learning to recognize them, consider their effects on his psyche, and ultimately to value them deeply.

195
00:23:45,022 --> 00:23:50,108
We can sensitize ourselves to these notions in a variation on metta meditation.

196
00:23:51,550 --> 00:24:00,241
Instead of repeating phrases of goodwill, we can repeat a phrase like no harm as we think of people in all the usual metta categories.

197
00:24:01,502 --> 00:24:04,446
We can do the same thing for the phrase no cruelty.

198
00:24:06,328 --> 00:24:14,980
Both of these exercises help us to value the fairly neutral states we often experience in meditation or during quiet moments in life.

199
00:24:16,022 --> 00:24:24,070
It's easy to overlook these, but when we reflect on their peaceful, non-threatening nature, it deepens our appreciation.

200
00:24:27,433 --> 00:24:38,344
Thoughts of non-ill will and non-cruelty will arise spontaneously when we're letting go of their opposites, though again it's easy to overlook these in the heat of the moment.

201
00:24:39,744 --> 00:24:45,590
Suppose we've gone through a bout of rage and have been gloating over the details of the punishment we're going to dish out.

202
00:24:46,397 --> 00:24:55,030
We've gone from rage to cruelty here, but sooner or later a bit of wisdom will return to suggest that we might be straying off the path a tiny bit.

203
00:24:56,752 --> 00:25:04,144
There may then be the tendency to shoot straight into self-judgment and writhe in shame because of having succumbed to anger and cruelty.

204
00:25:05,205 --> 00:25:07,950
We might even despise ourselves in these moments.

205
00:25:08,790 --> 00:25:21,823
But the Buddha is asking us instead to fish out any thoughts of deciding not to enact all our delicious punishments, to single these out from the rest of the turmoil and look on them with appreciation.

206
00:25:24,826 --> 00:25:31,251
At some stage in the transition from rage to self-judgment, there is the decision to stop feeding the rage.

207
00:25:32,633 --> 00:25:37,718
This decision may have come with a thought like, this is getting me nowhere, I'll have to stop.

208
00:25:38,946 --> 00:25:46,969
It would be easy to forget that thought as the mind sinks into despair or ricochets into self-judgment.

209
00:25:46,989 --> 00:25:55,250
To sensitize ourselves to such thoughts, we can steady our attention around the feelings associated with these.

210
00:25:56,480 --> 00:26:09,311
This will have the added benefit of stemming the proliferation of the competing negative thoughts which may revolve around despair, self-judgment, blame, guilt or shame and the odd ricochet back to rage.

211
00:26:10,593 --> 00:26:26,487
Thus, paying attention to the thread of wholesome thought will effectively contain our negativity and we might start to feel better about ourselves, more confident that we can learn to work with anger and not let it harm ourselves or others.

212
00:26:28,356 --> 00:26:33,142
So what do thoughts of non-ill will, non-cruelty actually feel like?

213
00:26:34,884 --> 00:26:36,486
I find these very subtle.

214
00:26:37,267 --> 00:26:45,616
A quiet withdrawal of energy from that strong sense of self that builds around anger or its ricochet into self-judgment and shame.

215
00:26:47,157 --> 00:26:54,886
The body seems to shrink a fraction during those thoughts and there is a momentary relaxation, a sense of withdrawing.

216
00:26:56,385 --> 00:27:00,454
There is a danger of shrinking further into shame and fear of judgment.

217
00:27:01,517 --> 00:27:17,009
But if I can detect the wish to shrink and resist it, the negative energies drain into that midway state of quietness and a sense of confidence starts to work its way through the shame, strengthening the no harm attitude.

218
00:27:19,420 --> 00:27:26,609
In that more stable emotional state, I might find the mental space to repeat the Buddha's suggested phrases.

219
00:27:27,751 --> 00:27:30,335
This thought does not lead to my affliction.

220
00:27:32,357 --> 00:27:42,271
This usually increases confidence, adds an element of joy, suggests that despite all my failings, I might be on the right path.

221
00:27:44,092 --> 00:27:51,682
By comparison, the reflection, this thought does not lead to others' affliction, is more challenging for my psyche.

222
00:27:52,744 --> 00:28:03,380
I still get the extra boost of confidence and joy, but the desire to collapse into shame also increases as I start to acknowledge the harm I'd been planning for my enemy.

223
00:28:04,741 --> 00:28:13,575
The third phrase, this thought does not lead to the affliction of both, brings more stability and a determination to mend my ways.

224
00:28:15,192 --> 00:28:25,102
As mentioned earlier, this contemplation of self and other lets the positive energy from the wiser response support the weaker response.

225
00:28:26,403 --> 00:28:40,457
The final phrase, this thought aids wisdom, does not cause difficulties, leads to nibbana, usually deepens my remorse and determination not to indulge anger in future.

226
00:28:43,609 --> 00:28:48,055
We can work in exactly the same way regarding thoughts of renouncing sense desire.

227
00:28:49,797 --> 00:28:57,105
Following my acknowledgement of the afflictions brought by worries about Katie and Kieran, I decided not to watch Fair City that evening.

228
00:28:58,528 --> 00:29:04,535
It would have been very easy to just nod my head wisely and with a touch of shame for needing to make such a decision.

229
00:29:05,655 --> 00:29:12,924
But when I repeated, this thought does not lead to my affliction, I noticed a pleasant feeling of relief.

230
00:29:13,916 --> 00:29:20,290
A touch of pride was added to the relief when I reflected, this thought does not lead to the affliction of others.

231
00:29:22,154 --> 00:29:30,053
A sense of self-care was added to the mix when I reflected, this thought does not lead to either my own or others affliction.

232
00:29:31,535 --> 00:29:44,175
The final phrase, this thought aids wisdom, does not cause difficulties, leads to Nibbana, brought a sense of happiness and deepened the commitment to the decision.

233
00:29:47,201 --> 00:29:54,673
With regard to these wise thoughts of renunciation, non-ill will and non-cruelty, the Buddha adds this interesting reflection.

234
00:29:57,673 --> 00:30:07,288
If I think and ponder upon this thought, even for a night, even for a day, even for a day and a night, I see nothing to fear from it.

235
00:30:08,569 --> 00:30:20,906
But with excessive thinking and pondering, I might tire my body, and when the body is tired, the mind becomes strained, and when the mind is strained, it is far from concentration.

236
00:30:21,949 --> 00:30:24,271
So I steady to my mind internally,

237
00:30:24,640 --> 00:30:41,686
He expands on his simile of the cowherd to clarify this.

238
00:30:44,096 --> 00:31:10,509
just as in the last month of the hot season when all the crops have been brought inside the villages a cowherd would guard his cows while staying at the root of a tree or out in the open since he only needs to be mindful that the cows are there so too there was need only for me to be mindful that wholesome states were there in the case of unwholesome thoughts

239
00:31:10,759 --> 00:31:16,958
We are to be like a cowherd in the rainy season, poking at them with a stick to prevent them doing harm.

240
00:31:18,041 --> 00:31:25,343
But with wholesome thoughts, we can take it easy, just noticing these without any effort to control or develop them.

241
00:31:28,866 --> 00:31:34,699
This, in effect, confirms that our natural, relaxed state is inherently wholesome.

242
00:31:35,840 --> 00:31:38,646
We don't need to control, protect or develop it.

243
00:31:39,568 --> 00:31:41,472
All we need do is notice it.

244
00:31:42,694 --> 00:31:44,157
It's a very comforting thought.

245
00:31:46,467 --> 00:31:51,314
This also ties in with what we spoke of in the Sutta on the raft.

246
00:31:51,334 --> 00:31:54,898
Once we've crossed the flood, we have to let go of the raft.

247
00:31:55,740 --> 00:31:58,123
We shouldn't try to cling to wholesome states.

248
00:31:58,743 --> 00:32:02,189
We will only tie ourselves out and put our minds under strain.

249
00:32:03,471 --> 00:32:08,176
Awareness is not troubled by the unwholesome and does not depend on the wholesome.

250
00:32:11,080 --> 00:32:12,963
Let's recap with an example.

251
00:32:13,972 --> 00:32:16,896
Say you decide not to have an extra slice of cake.

252
00:32:18,137 --> 00:32:27,089
Don't let this go unacknowledged amidst what might be posing as more righteous thoughts like, of course I don't need an extra slice, how could I be so greedy?

253
00:32:28,531 --> 00:32:31,776
These righteous thoughts reflect an overshoot into condemnation.

254
00:32:33,017 --> 00:32:39,846
In condemning our desire for cake, we are unwittingly condemning ourselves for having desires, thinking, I am greedy.

255
00:32:41,007 --> 00:32:45,873
But the energy of desire itself can be directed towards the goal of our spiritual life.

256
00:32:46,653 --> 00:32:48,276
We don't want to suppress this.

257
00:32:49,016 --> 00:32:50,097
We want to use it.

258
00:32:52,460 --> 00:33:03,993
What we need to find is the middle ground where the basic energy of desire is known and our only job is to check that it's not directed towards false hopes of happiness.

259
00:33:05,509 --> 00:33:12,306
Like our cowherd in the rainy season, we poke at it with a stick, saying, This thought will lead to my affliction.

260
00:33:13,127 --> 00:33:19,823
For as long as thoughts of having more cake are nudging us to pick up a knife and cut that extra slice.

261
00:33:20,561 --> 00:33:28,316
When we feel a change of heart and are no longer edging towards the knife, happy to renounce cake, we can relax.

262
00:33:29,417 --> 00:33:35,849
Like the cowherd in the dry season, we simply notice the contented state for as long as it lasts.

263
00:33:37,092 --> 00:33:42,823
In this way, we direct our instinctive desire for happiness towards its true goal.

264
00:33:46,532 --> 00:33:54,063
The Buddha closes the Sutta with another pastoral simile which this time gives us a broad brush image for our spiritual life.

265
00:33:54,943 --> 00:33:55,984
Here are his words.

266
00:33:58,949 --> 00:34:07,900
Suppose Bhikkhus that in a wooded range there was a great low-lying marsh near which a large herd of deer lived.

267
00:34:09,230 --> 00:34:31,407
Then a man appeared desiring their ruin, harm and bondage, and he closed off the safe and good path that led to their happiness, and he opened up a false path, and he put out a decoy and set up a dummy, so that the large herd of deer would later come upon calamity, disaster and loss.

268
00:34:32,820 --> 00:34:42,117
But another man came, desirous of their good, welfare and protection, and he reopened the safe and good path that led to their happiness.

269
00:34:43,239 --> 00:34:55,943
And he closed off the false path, and he removed the decoy and destroyed the dummy, so that the large herd of deer could later come to growth, increase and fulfilment.

270
00:34:59,516 --> 00:35:08,369
The herd of deer represents living beings while Mara, the personification of evil in Buddhism, closes off the safe path.

271
00:35:09,690 --> 00:35:14,277
The marsh represents sensual pleasure and sensual desire is the decoy.

272
00:35:15,498 --> 00:35:22,327
If your mind likes working with images, try imagining a trail of lush vegetation luring the deer toward the marsh.

273
00:35:23,690 --> 00:35:25,052
Ignorance is the dummy.

274
00:35:26,246 --> 00:35:33,681
I imagine a scarecrow in the shape of a wolf that blocks off the noble eightfold path that leads to happiness.

275
00:35:35,023 --> 00:35:43,900
It is the Buddha who removes the decoy of lush vegetation and destroys the scarewolf, thereby reopening the eightfold path.

276
00:35:46,445 --> 00:35:49,791
The parallel here with Christian imagery is striking.

277
00:35:50,394 --> 00:35:55,942
In the Christian myth we have Lucifer, the devil, causing the rift between God and mankind.

278
00:35:56,963 --> 00:36:06,076
The rift is then healed by Christ, the Good Shepherd, who cares for us, his flock, and sets up a new covenant between God and mankind.

279
00:36:08,398 --> 00:36:15,188
This image of the deer herd fits very well with the Buddha's teaching on Kalyanamita, or spiritual friendship.

280
00:36:17,007 --> 00:36:27,128
To allow such friendships form the whole of the spiritual life, we are to see the Buddha as our spiritual friend and develop a loving relationship with him.

281
00:36:28,351 --> 00:36:34,965
The simile of the deer herd provides quite a beautiful image we can use for such a devotional practice.

282
00:36:37,291 --> 00:36:50,715
The whole notion of devotion may turn some of you off, but if, like me, you were brought up with the family rosary, this simile could be a very helpful way of integrating your Christian heritage within Buddhist practice.

283
00:36:52,137 --> 00:37:01,695
And since two separate religions have come up with such a strikingly similar image for spiritual development, I think there must be something worthwhile here.

284
00:37:06,686 --> 00:37:11,172
The Good Shepherd image might not appeal to everyone as it likens us to a flock of sheep.

285
00:37:12,172 --> 00:37:18,219
A deer herd is a bit easier on our sensitivities and I'm finding this image very useful.

286
00:37:19,860 --> 00:37:29,170
Rather than go through all the phrases on affliction, I sometimes picture the Buddha picking up the lush vegetation that is tempting me to take the wrong path.

287
00:37:30,411 --> 00:37:36,237
So far, I still find the notion of Mara quite challenging, though I can see the value of this.

288
00:37:37,670 --> 00:37:44,396
It's easy to gloss over the perils of sensual pleasure when we live within a society that actively promotes these.

289
00:37:45,699 --> 00:37:52,425
Imagining a leering devil lurking behind the TV during the ads wakes me up to the danger these pose.

290
00:37:53,666 --> 00:37:56,911
It focuses the mind to think that someone is really out to get you.

291
00:37:58,693 --> 00:38:03,458
Our minds are good at enmity, so we might as well put that talent to a useful purpose.

292
00:38:06,407 --> 00:38:20,369
To balance this, we have the image of the Buddha desiring our welfare and happiness, removing the allure of sensual pleasures with his teaching, destroying the scarewolf of ignorance that blocks our path to happiness.

293
00:38:21,811 --> 00:38:27,059
See if you find it helpful to let your imagination play around with the image of the deer herd.

294
00:38:28,079 --> 00:38:31,284
And don't forget the other pastoral image given in this sutta.

295
00:38:32,614 --> 00:38:40,804
Like the cowherd in the rainy season, we prod at unskilful thoughts with wise reflections on the danger they pose.

296
00:38:42,146 --> 00:38:51,818
When wholesome thoughts appear, we relax, like the cowherd in the dry season, noticing these without tiring ourselves out by pondering them.

297
00:38:54,822 --> 00:38:59,887
Just before closing, I want to remind you of this very striking line from the Sutta.

298
00:39:01,824 --> 00:39:08,597
Whatever a bhikkhu frequently thinks and ponders upon, that will become the inclination of his mind.

299
00:39:11,101 --> 00:39:13,065
Let's bring that home to ourselves.

300
00:39:14,347 --> 00:39:20,458
Whatever we frequently think and ponder upon, that will become the inclination of our mind.

301
00:39:23,947 --> 00:39:34,751
May we develop a wise relationship with thoughts and thereby avoid the alluring swamp of sense pleasure and find the true path to happiness.

